Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from the persistent challenge in semi-supervised learning (SSL) of effectively leveraging unlabeled data without amplifying confirmation bias or overfitting to incorrect pseudo-labels—especially under class imbalance. While contrastive self-training (CST) has shown promise by combining representation learning with pseudo-labeling, it often struggles to balance confidence and generalization due to static temperature scaling in the softmax distribution used for pseudo-label generation. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s use of self-training for counterfactual imputation and Paper 2’s integration of contrastive signals into dynamic model components (e.g., attention), I propose embedding meta-learning into the temperature adaptation mechanism. This would allow the model to *learn how to adjust temperature dynamically* based on uncertainty, class frequency, and representation consistency across epochs—particularly crucial in imbalanced settings where rare classes are easily overwhelmed by high-confidence dominant ones. Unlike heuristic temperature schedules, a meta-learned controller can adaptively modulate the sharpness of prediction distributions to promote both exploration (via softer distributions early on) and exploitation (via sharper ones later), while preventing premature convergence to biased pseudo-labels. Furthermore, integrating a contrastive loss that operates on both labeled and confidently pseudo-labeled samples ensures that decision boundaries are informed not just by label predictions but also by semantic similarity—a synergy underexplored in current adaptive SSL frameworks. The novelty lies in unifying meta-learning with temperature control within a contrastive self-training loop, creating a feedback system where the learning dynamics themselves are optimized for long-term generalization rather than short-term accuracy gains.

