  "Idea": "We propose a novel paradigm titled 'Self-Conditioned Adaptive Temperature Modulation (SCATM)' for contrastive self-training, which eliminates the need for external meta-controllers by embedding adaptive temperature learning directly within the model's inference pipeline. Instead of relying on a separate LSTM-based meta-learner to suggest temperature values based on epoch-level statistics, SCATM equips the primary model with a lightweight context aggregation and gating module that operates at the batch level. This module collects real-time signals such as per-class prediction entropy, inter-augmentation consistency, pseudo-label stability over recent epochs, and estimated label distribution skew. These signals are encoded into a compact context vector, which is then used to generate class-specific or sample-wise temperature scalars via a small learnable gating network (e.g., a single-layer MLP with sigmoid activation). Crucially, the gating network is trained end-to-end alongside the main model using a validation-aware meta-objective: during training, a small held-out labeled set is used to compute a differentiable proxy of generalization performance (e.g., cross-entropy loss), which guides the backpropagation of gradients through the temperature pathway. To prevent interference between representation learning and calibration, we decouple the contrastive and classification objectives following a dual-head architecture—one head handles supervised and pseudo-labeled classification with adaptive temperature scaling, while the other performs contrastive learning using only high-confidence samples selected via the same temperature-gated confidence measure. This ensures that noisy pseudo-labels do not corrupt the feature space. Moreover, SCATM introduces a memory buffer to track historical prediction patterns per class, enabling long-term adaptation especially for rare classes that appear infrequently. By internalizing the meta-learning signal, SCATM achieves faster convergence, better transfer across datasets, and improved robustness to imbalance without increasing architectural complexity. We expect this method to outperform both fixed-temperature and externally controlled baselines, particularly in low-label regimes (<100 labeled examples) and extreme imbalance (ratio >100), while offering greater transparency through interpretable context-to-temperature mappings.",
